ing his tenure at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Bryn_Mawr_College\" title=\"Bryn Mawr College\">Bryn Mawr<\/a>. Following the rediscovery of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mendelian_inheritance\" title=\"Mendelian inheritance\">Mendelian inheritance<\/a> in 1900, Morgan's research moved to the study of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mutation\" title=\"Mutation\">mutation<\/a> in the fruit fly <i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Drosophila_melanogaster\" title=\"Drosophila melanogaster\">Drosophila melanogaster<\/a><\/i>. In his famous Fly Room at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Columbia_University\" title=\"Columbia University\">Columbia University<\/a>, Morgan demonstrated that <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Gene\" title=\"Gene\">genes<\/a> are carried on <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Chromosome\" title=\"Chromosome\">chromosomes<\/a> and are the mechanical basis of heredity. These discoveries formed the basis of the modern science of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Genetics\" title=\"Genetics\">genetics<\/a>.<\/p><p>During his distinguished career, Morgan wrote <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/List_of_books_by_Thomas_Hunt_Morgan\" title=\"List of books by Thomas Hunt Morgan\" class=\"mw-redirect\">22 books<\/a> and 370 scientific papers.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Fisher_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Thomas_H._Morgan#cite_note-Fisher-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> As a result of his work, <i>Drosophila<\/i> became a major <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Model_organism\" title=\"Model organism\">model organism<\/a> in contemporary genetics. The Division of Biology which he established at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/California_Institute_of_Technology\" title=\"California Institute of Technology\">California Institute of Technology<\/a> has produced seven Nobel Prize winners.<\/p>","name":"Thomas H. Morgan","place_of_birth":"Lexington, Kentucky","place_of_death":"Pasadena, California","text":"Thomas H. Morgan , Physiology or Medicine, 1933","year":1933.0}